description: These sequestrate fungi were found in the duff beneath Arctostaphylos sp. in an area with Pinus jeffreyi.

Pterospora andromedea They live in a parasitic relationship with mycorrhizal fungi, in which plants derive all their carbon from their associated fungus, but the relationship is not yet well understood. The term for this kind of symbiosis is mycoheterotrophy. In Pteropspora the association is with a very limited number of fungi in the genus Rhizopogon Pterospora has consistently been shown to be more closely related to Sarcodes than any other member of the Monotropoidiae Source http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pterospora accessed 2 October 2013 Forest, Trail to Spray Park Mount Rainier National Park Northwestern Chapter of North American Rock Garden Society (NARGS) field trip s20130909 237

description: Small cluster of 7-8 fruiting bodies. Pale gray gleba. Outer surface yellowish and cracked.  Growing at drip line of planted ponderosa pine on grassy bank of school ground.  I sent images to Jim Trappe. Matt Trappe also weighed in with his opinion but Jim prevailed. His response follows:  Rhizopogon occidentalis is covered with   rhizomorphs covering the surface and usually doesn't turn pink where exposed. However, a lookalike species in SW Oregon does develop brick red patches as it ages. I think of those two as "the R. occidentalis complex."  images remind me very much of the R. rubescens-R. vulgaris complex. R. rubescens has lots of adpressed rhizomorphs and in youth stains the pretty pink of Scott's images.  R. vulgaris is similar but devoid of surface rhizomorphs. Its spores also are smaller than R. rubescens. Trouble is, the images show a very few and rather inconspicuous surface rhizomorphs, so it is half way between the two species. Spore size is needed.  the images remind me or a pogie that emerges iunder the pines that have overtaken the old Stehekin schoolhouse. I have called that one R. vulgaris, but these and the several related species need to be sorted out by molecular  methods.  The species discussed above prefer pines to any other trees.

description: in soil next to Pinus ponderosa

NAMP #	08124

DATE:	03, 08, & 27 DEC 2018

STATE:	WA

COUNTY:	PIERCE

FORAY ID:	Mycoflora Project.

SITE NAME:	McChord Air Force Base, Lakewood, WA

iNat #:	31948559

NEARBY FLORA:	Douglas Fir.

SUBSTRATE:	Dense Humus Soil, Needle Duff, Grass, Moss.

HABIT:	Single to Few to Many (as many as 8 within 1-foot area).

LIGHT EXPOSURE: 	Partial shade to full sun (50% of day)

ODOR:	Mild Musky, pleasant smell.

TASTE:	Nutty, mild.

REFERENCES:	Mushrooms of the Redwood Coast (Siegel & Schwarz), pg 543; 
	
DETAILED PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION: 

FRUIT BODY:
	1 – 4 cm across/long, sometimes round-ish or ovoid, but always irregularly shaped...very much like a Jerusalem Artichoke Bulb.  Color varies based on age, from dingy white to grayish, to a dirty pink distributed irregularly on the surface.  The oldest specimens are nearly black.  The surface is dry, even with rains.  The surface is somewhat Tomentose which is matted.  .  

INTERIOR:
	Firm, Rubbery, sponge-like but very tight, of a light grey-green Mossy color with dark-brown blobs in some specimens. With age, they turn a medium Rusty Brown, and eventually turn a dark grey-green.

SPORES:	Ostensibly pale yellow.

MYCELIA:	Black, matted, hairy-like, and about 1 cm long, if present.

description:
Fresh cluster came up today in the “mushroom pile” area of our yard. We have a corner of the yard where our young persimmon sapling is growing that has become the mushroom spot for all old or inedible fruiting bodies for the last few seasons(corner fence w/very little sun exposure). This week the species happened to be small mica caps against the fence. I have found Geastrum spp., Rhizopogon app., Marasmius oreades, Lycoperdon, Scleroderma and multiple species of Agaricus in our yard so far in the last two seasons. Not positive, but pretty convinced our throwing of these wild species in the urban setting have brought them up over time at this current location.

There are three distinctly different mica caps that fruit in Yakima, WA throughout the year from my personal observation; A very small version that looks identical to the West side of WA fruiters(thin long stem, shiny., a floccose version that is much stouter and shorter(caps are almost not visible due to paper thin floccose skin surrounding fruitbodies, and finally, this species that exhibits the mica dust on cap AND the flocking on margins and young fruit bodies.

I’m looking forward to seeing what other species of fungi will show up and out compete local fungal residents in the yard – hopefully, most of them will come up throughout the remainder of this Spring/Summer season in our ever evolving “mushroom spot.”

Elevation: 1500ft.

Temp: 78, sunny. Low 80’s over the last three days.

UPDATED 5/8/15: Images of fully mature specimens four days after beginning of visible flush. The caps still exhibit the tenuous flocculant(with striation) behavior as with C.flocculosus, but also have mica looking dust on young specimens. I am leaning more toward C.flocculosus after updated growth5/8. Very large at maturity- fully expanded caps approx. 4cm wide.

Updated 5/29/15: Notes below each additional image.

UPDATED 6/12/15: New satellite of primordial young buttons coming up in caespitose lumps near the ever growing persimmon. This strains mycelium has gone down the fence in three different directions for over a month now. Whenever I water, they pop up to spread more spores.

description:
Found beneath young saplings of Douglas fir, Western hemlock and Western red cedar(all within five feet of Hypogeus sample).

Elevation: 5000ft.

Temp: low 70’s.

Note: Was going to try and slice this down the middle to show inner context(as I usually do with truffles and false truffles), but the damn thing was rock solid from drought. I have kept the specimen, vouchered, bagged and will study further.

Bone white, slight pinkish brown discoloration on lower portions of gleba. Small evident pigtail stem in center of sporophore-perhaps rhizopogon? Will delve further once I can crack the thing open.
